In {{ill|907 AD|ja|907th year|12=draft}} (the 7th year of {{ill|Engi|ja|延喜|12=draft}}), the deity {{ill|Hachimangu|ja|八幡神|12=draft}} was enshrined by invitation from {{ill|Usa Shrine|ja|宇佐神宮|12=draft}} of Buzen Province and merged with the shrine, which then became known as Moriyama Hachimangu.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="srg"/>
In August {{ill|1180 AD|ja|1180th year|12=draft}} (the 4th year of {{ill|Jishō|ja|治承|12=draft}}), when {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft}} prayed for the defeat of the Taira clan and rallied his forces, several dozen of his soldiers attacked the mansion of {{ill|Yamaki Kanetaka|ja|山木兼隆|12=draft}}, located near what would later become the Nirayama Daikan-sho, and the ensuing flames were observed from this site.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="kk"/>
The current main hall was constructed in {{ill|1632 AD|ja|1632nd year|12=draft}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Kannen|ja|寛永|12=draft}}) by Sakakibara Teruhisa, the lord of {{ill|Kunō Castle|ja|久能城|12=draft}}, and replaced an earlier structure from 1597 (the 2nd year of {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|12=draft}}) by the lord of Nirayama Castle, Naitō Nobunari.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="sbs"/><ref name="hjs">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/2-4houjounosato-huuti.pdf Historical Aesthetics along the Old Shimoda Kaidō, as seen in Izunokuni City] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref>
The stage hall was constructed in {{ill|1934 AD|ja|1934th year|12=draft}} (Showa 9).<ref name="rts"/><ref name="sbs"/>

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Hota Wakabetsu-no-Mikoto|ja|誉田別命|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|ja|大山祇神|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Konohananosakuyahime-no-Mikoto|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|12=draft}}

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds include:
* Main Hall and Haiden
* Stage Hall and its accompanying Haiden
* A monument commemorating {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft}}’s military expedition
* Torii

