'''Moriyama Hachimangu''' (守山八幡宮, もりやまはちまんぐう) is a Shinto shrine located in Izunokuni City, {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuoka Prefecture|qq=}}. It is one of the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=}} of Izu Province and a successor shrine of {{ill|Iwatokotake Shrine|ja|石徳高神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwatokotake Shrine|qq=}} (also read as {{ill|Iwato Kotakejinja|ja|いわとこたけじんじゃ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwato Kotakejinja|qq=}}) along with {{ill|Mugatsuka Shrine|ja|豆塚神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mugatsuka Shrine|qq=}}, which is situated in the western, Emma district across the {{ill|Kano River|ja|狩野川|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kano River|qq=}}. It is also known as the shrine where {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} rallied his forces and prayed for the defeat of the Taira clan.<ref name="yuisho">(Shrine legend document)</ref><ref name="kk">[https://izunotabi.com/sightseeing/moriyama-hachimangu/ Moriyama Hachimangu] - {{ill|Izunokuni City Tourism Association|ja|伊豆の国市観光協会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izunokuni City Tourism Association|qq=}}</ref><ref name="srg">[https://www.surugawan.net/guide/333.html Moriyama Hachimangu] - {{ill|Izu Suruga Tourism Guide|ja|伊豆駿河観光ガイド|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izu Suruga Tourism Guide|qq=}}</ref>

== Overview ==
The shrine is located in the mountainous area of Moriyama, in the western part of the Terake district (formerly known as {{ill|Nirayama Town|ja|韮山町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nirayama Town|qq=}}) of Izunokuni City. This area is home to a concentration of historical sites related to the {{ill|Hōjō family|ja|北条家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōjō family|qq=}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}}, as well as remains of the 【伝堀越御所跡】 from the Muromachi period.

The shrine grounds are arranged in two levels. Immediately after ascending a flight of stone steps, one encounters the stage hall and the haiden. Beyond these, an additional 142 steep stone steps lead to the main hall and another haiden.<ref name="kk"/>
At the lower stage hall, during the annual grand festival in October, rituals such as the Shagiri and the offering of the "Sambansō" are performed.<ref name="rts">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/nisyu32.pdf Moriyama Hachimangu and the Grand Festival] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref><ref name="sbs">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/2-7nirayama-oohito.pdf Historical Aesthetics of Festival Rituals and Sambansō in the Nirayama-Oohito Area] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref>

== History ==
The shrine was founded in {{ill|647 AD|ja|647th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/647 AD|qq=}} (the 3rd year of {{ill|Taika|ja|大化|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taika|qq=}}), enshrining {{ill|Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|ja|大山祇神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|qq=}}. It later became a Shikinaisha in Izu Province through its association with Iwatokotake Shrine.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="srg"/>
In {{ill|907 AD|ja|907th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/907 AD|qq=}} (the 7th year of {{ill|Engi|ja|延喜|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engi|qq=}}), the deity {{ill|Hachimangu|ja|八幡神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachimangu|qq=}} was enshrined by invitation from {{ill|Usa Shrine|ja|宇佐神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Usa Shrine|qq=}} of Buzen Province and merged with the shrine, which then became known as Moriyama Hachimangu.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="srg"/>
In August {{ill|1180 AD|ja|1180th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1180 AD|qq=}} (the 4th year of {{ill|Jishō|ja|治承|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jishō|qq=}}), when {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} prayed for the defeat of the Taira clan and rallied his forces, several dozen of his soldiers attacked the mansion of {{ill|Yamaki Kanetaka|ja|山木兼隆|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaki Kanetaka|qq=}}, located near what would later become the Nirayama Daikan-sho, and the ensuing flames were observed from this site.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="kk"/>
The current main hall was constructed in {{ill|1632 AD|ja|1632nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1632 AD|qq=}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Kannen|ja|寛永|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannen|qq=}}) by Sakakibara Teruhisa, the lord of {{ill|Kunō Castle|ja|久能城|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunō Castle|qq=}}, and replaced an earlier structure from 1597 (the 2nd year of {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō|qq=}}) by the lord of Nirayama Castle, Naitō Nobunari.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="sbs"/><ref name="hjs">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/2-4houjounosato-huuti.pdf Historical Aesthetics along the Old Shimoda Kaidō, as seen in Izunokuni City] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref>
The stage hall was constructed in {{ill|1934 AD|ja|1934th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1934 AD|qq=}} (Showa 9).<ref name="rts"/><ref name="sbs"/>

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Hota Wakabetsu-no-Mikoto|ja|誉田別命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hota Wakabetsu-no-Mikoto|qq=}}
* {{ill|Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|ja|大山祇神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|qq=}}
* {{ill|Konohananosakuyahime-no-Mikoto|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohananosakuyahime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=}}

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds include:
* Main Hall and Haiden
* Stage Hall and its accompanying Haiden
* A monument commemorating {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}}’s military expedition
* Torii

