'''Moriyama Hachimangu''' (守山八幡宮, もりやまはちまんぐう) is a Shinto shrine located in Izunokuni City, [[:en:Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]]. It is one of the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 延喜式神名帳}} of Izu Province and a successor shrine of {{ill|Iwatokotake Shrine|ja|石徳高神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwatokotake Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (also read as {{ill|Iwato Kotakejinja|ja|いわとこたけじんじゃ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwato Kotakejinja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}) along with {{ill|Mugatsuka Shrine|ja|豆塚神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mugatsuka Shrine|qq=}}, which is situated in the western, Emma district across the [[:en:Kano River|Kano River]]. It is also known as the shrine where [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]] rallied his forces and prayed for the defeat of the Taira clan.<ref name="yuisho">(Shrine legend document)</ref><ref name="kk">[https://izunotabi.com/sightseeing/moriyama-hachimangu/ Moriyama Hachimangu] - {{ill|Izunokuni City Tourism Association|ja|伊豆の国市観光協会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izunokuni City Tourism Association|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}</ref><ref name="srg">[https://www.surugawan.net/guide/333.html Moriyama Hachimangu] - {{ill|Izu Suruga Tourism Guide|ja|伊豆駿河観光ガイド|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izu Suruga Tourism Guide|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}</ref>

== Overview ==
The shrine is located in the mountainous area of Moriyama, in the western part of the Terake district (formerly known as [[:en:Nirayama, Shizuoka|Nirayama Town]]) of Izunokuni City. This area is home to a concentration of historical sites related to the {{ill|Hōjō family|ja|北条家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōjō family|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 北条氏 (曖昧さ回避)}} and [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]], as well as remains of the 【伝堀越御所跡】 from the Muromachi period.

The shrine grounds are arranged in two levels. Immediately after ascending a flight of stone steps, one encounters the stage hall and the haiden. Beyond these, an additional 142 steep stone steps lead to the main hall and another haiden.<ref name="kk"/>
At the lower stage hall, during the annual grand festival in October, rituals such as the Shagiri and the offering of the "Sambansō" are performed.<ref name="rts">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/nisyu32.pdf Moriyama Hachimangu and the Grand Festival] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref><ref name="sbs">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/2-7nirayama-oohito.pdf Historical Aesthetics of Festival Rituals and Sambansō in the Nirayama-Oohito Area] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref>

== History ==
The shrine was founded in [[:en:647|647 AD]] (the 3rd year of [[:en:Taika (era)|Taika]]), enshrining {{ill|Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|ja|大山祇神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to オオヤマツミ}}. It later became a Shikinaisha in Izu Province through its association with Iwatokotake Shrine.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="srg"/>
In [[:en:907|907 AD]] (the 7th year of [[:en:Engi (era)|Engi]]), the deity [[:en:Hachiman|Hachimangu]] was enshrined by invitation from [[:en:Usa Jingū|Usa Shrine]] of Buzen Province and merged with the shrine, which then became known as Moriyama Hachimangu.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="srg"/>
In August [[:en:1180|1180 AD]] (the 4th year of [[:en:Jishō|Jishō]]), when [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]] prayed for the defeat of the Taira clan and rallied his forces, several dozen of his soldiers attacked the mansion of {{ill|Yamaki Kanetaka|ja|山木兼隆|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamaki Kanetaka|qq=}}, located near what would later become the Nirayama Daikan-sho, and the ensuing flames were observed from this site.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="kk"/>
The current main hall was constructed in [[:en:1632|1632 AD]] (the 9th year of [[:en:Kan'ei|Kannen]]) by Sakakibara Teruhisa, the lord of {{ill|Kunō Castle|ja|久能城|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunō Castle|qq=}}, and replaced an earlier structure from 1597 (the 2nd year of [[:en:Keichō|Keichō]]) by the lord of Nirayama Castle, Naitō Nobunari.<ref name="yuisho"/><ref name="sbs"/><ref name="hjs">[https://www.city.izunokuni.shizuoka.jp/tosikei/documents/2-4houjounosato-huuti.pdf Historical Aesthetics along the Old Shimoda Kaidō, as seen in Izunokuni City] - Izunokuni City Urban Planning Division</ref>
The stage hall was constructed in [[:en:1934|1934 AD]] (Showa 9).<ref name="rts"/><ref name="sbs"/>

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Hota Wakabetsu-no-Mikoto|ja|誉田別命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hota Wakabetsu-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 応神天皇}}
* {{ill|Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|ja|大山祇神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyama Tsumi-no-Kami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to オオヤマツミ}}
* {{ill|Konohananosakuyahime-no-Mikoto|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohananosakuyahime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to コノハナノサクヤビメ}}

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds include:
* Main Hall and Haiden
* Stage Hall and its accompanying Haiden
* A monument commemorating [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]]’s military expedition
* Torii

